<article id="post-694" class="post-694 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-student-focus category-study-abroad tag-internships tag-olympics">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/an-internship-of-olympic-proportions/" rel="bookmark">An Internship of Olympic Proportions</a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/an-internship-of-olympic-proportions/" title="Permalink to An Internship of Olympic Proportions" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2014-05-05T20:24:52+00:00">May 5, 2014</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<div id="attachment_695" style="width: 680px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-8.22.36-PM.png"><img class="wp-image-695 size-full" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-8.22.36-PM.png" alt="O’Connell meeting Team USA gold medalist in slopestyle  snowboarding Sage Kotsenburg." width="670" height="521" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">O’Connell meeting Team USA gold medalist in slopestyle<br /> snowboarding Sage Kotsenburg.</p></div>
<p>After being offered a chance to work at the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi, Russia, as an intern for NBCUniversal, Cai O’Connell—a junior Russian and political science double major—was able to experience the world in ways that she had never before imagined. For three weeks in February, O’Connell served as a translator and Olympic guide. While there, she also had the opportunity to see Russian President Vladimir Putin and meet US Olympians such as figure skater Gracie Gold and snowboarder Sage Kotsenburg.</p>
<p>Although O’Connell’s incredible experience just happened this year, the arduous and long road that culminated in this Olympic opportunity began in her full-immersion Russian classroom at the Illinois Math and Science Academy. After her time there, O’Connell continued her studies at Cornell College before transferring to UIC. These years of academic Russian language training gave her an advantage in the three-month long interview process that eventually earned her the NBCUniversal internship. In addition to O’Connell’s language skills, she brought relevant work experience to the job through her previous internships with the Tenth Congressional District Democrats and Obama for America.</p>
<p>As an Olympic guide, O’Connell witnessed a variety of intense sports, such as ski jumping and curling. She also learned a lot about international events management and control. She observed<br />
how the Russian government ensured security for all guests and personnel with a multitude of security guards and airport-like security checks, as well as the censorship of certain websites.<br />
O’Connell herself was in charge of the safety of over 200 guests at a time and used her knowledge<br />
of Russian to not only eliminate communication barriers, but also to better understand the local<br />
and international guests at Sochi.</p>
<p>On March 19th, O’Connell delivered a presentation called “Sports, Sexuality, and International Politics: Sochi 2014” at the UIC Daley Library. She gave a joint talk with Brittany James, a UIC alumna who interned at Sochi with the International Olympic and the International Paralympic Committees. O’Connell discussed her responsibilities and also commented on the treatment of LGBT people and LGBT rights activists that she witnessed in the wake of the recent passing of anti-gay legislature in Russia. She recalls that “inside the Olympic arena, [neither] the LGBT community, nor many other groups, were allowed to protest.”</p>
<p>O’Connell admits that her time at the Olympics was not always easy. However, as she hopes to someday work in an embassy in Foreign Service Management, she stands by everything she learned at Sochi: “The experience of working in intense situations was worth it.”</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>by: Rafid Rahman, Freshman, Biological Sciences</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
			
		
